And this isn't even like, "Oh, maybe you *bricks* or *perverts* can go off HRT, but I, a delicate binary trans woman, can't!"

I'm a super bricky, fairly androgynous boymoder after  ~18 months. I'm not happy about it, but it's sustainable. Going off HRT is not.

// cw: suicide

My plan if I go off HRT is "kill myself" not because I've dramatised in my head what going off HRT will be like, but because I know what being off HRT and going off HRT is like. I'm hesitant about GCS because I'm not sure I can survive a month off HRT.

For the record it's still at "barely noticeable" levels. These days sometimes I go off ADHD meds for fun or to calm the fuck down. I could never have done that before.

I dunno if this is a normal reaction, nobody's studied that. I do know it happened to me, and I bet not only me

I can show that this is biologically plausible. I also know it happened to me because I withdrew just before starting HRT, with the effects described, and then again about two weeks after starting HRT. The second time was barely noticeable compared to the first.

I am sufficiently androgen-sensitive that I literally could not have my ADHD medication interrupted prior to HRT. Why? Because amphetamine is a very, very weak T blocker. Going off it meant not just normal withdrawal, but a spike in dissociation and dysphoria.

Pre-HRT, my career was choking to death because I had a suicidal meltdown every three weeks. One client I had then has unofficially blacklisted me because I couldn't go to a rehearsal I was supposed to be running because I'd been 5150ed. That wasn't sustainable.

Intersecting with but not directly in response to the "medication supply in anarchy" discourse: I think a lot of HRT-related discourse is informed by the fact that people have different experiences with HRT and some of us could absolutely give it up

But some of us can't
